<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="67" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,1396,1612]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,400,1396,1420]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1871" box="[413,631,1396,1420]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilitata">
<emphasis box="[413,631,1396,1420]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Apophylia nobilitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[851,928,1396,1420]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mila" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[851,928,1396,1420]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">A. mila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[935,1018,1397,1420]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Both species have a similar structure of the aedeagus and the apex of the last ventrite in female (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionTargetBox="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Figs. 1-3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[201,249,1460,1484]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1508,1527]" captionTargetBox="[140,1057,583,1477]" captionTargetId="figure-126@5.[140,1057,583,1477]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 9-13. Apophylia mila sp. nov. 9 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 10 – last ventrite of female; 11 – last ventrite and pygidium of female (lateral view); 12 – male metasternum; 13 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 9-11 and 13); 2 mm (Fig. 12)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174144/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">9-11</figureCitation>
). The male metasternum in 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[555,634,1460,1484]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mila" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[555,634,1460,1484]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">A. mila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[642,726,1461,1484]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
lacks teeth while it is bifurcate in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1871" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilitata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">A. nobilitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[270,388,1492,1516]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionTargetBox="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Figs. 4, 12</figureCitation>
). Moreover, tarsomere 1 of the hind tarsus is narrower in 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[1011,1088,1492,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mila" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1011,1088,1492,1516]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">A. mila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1871" box="[283,415,1524,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilitata">
<emphasis box="[283,415,1524,1548]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">A. nobilitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[430,545,1524,1548]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionTargetBox="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Figs. 5, 13</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="67" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,1396,1612]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,295,1556,1580]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[302,371,1557,1581]" name="Kenya" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Kenya</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[422,521,1556,1580]" name="Tanzania" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="ALFIERI A." box="[530,683,1556,1581]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" pagination="1 - 308" refId="ref8181" refString="ALFIERI A. 1976: The Coleoptera of Egypt. Memoires de la Societe Entomologique d'Egypte 5: 1 - 308." type="journal article" year="1976">ALFIERI (1976)</bibRefCitation>
listed it also from 
<collectingCountry box="[881,944,1557,1581]" name="Egypt" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Egypt</collectingCountry>
but this record is doubtful and probably refers to another species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1858" box="[689,798,1588,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[689,798,1588,1612]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Apophylia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="68" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,223,408]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,242,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68">Comments.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="GERSTAECKER A." box="[250,464,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" pagination="42 - 86" refId="ref8624" refString="GERSTAECKER A. 1871: Beitrag zur Insektenfauna von Zanzibar. III. Coleoptera. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 37: 42 - 86." type="journal article" year="1871">GERSTAECKER (1871)</bibRefCitation>
did not mention the number of available specimens in the original description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1871" box="[357,490,255,279]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilitata">
<emphasis box="[357,490,255,279]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="68">A. nobilitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Two years later he improved the description and stated that it was based on 
<specimenCount box="[343,490,287,311]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
(
<bibRefCitation author="GERSTAECKER A." box="[507,711,287,311]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refId="ref8648" refString="GERSTAECKER A. 1873: Die Gliederthier-Fauna des Sansibar-Gebietes. Nach dem von Dr. O. Kersten wahrend der v. d. Decken ' schen Ost-Afrikanischen Expedition im Jahre 1862 und von C. Cooke auf der Insel Sansibar im Jahre 1864 gesammelten Material. Bd. 3, Abth. 2. C. F. Winter, Leipzig &amp; Heidelberg, xii + 542 pp." type="book" year="1873">GERSTAECKER 1873</bibRefCitation>
). I had the possibility to study the female 
<typeStatus box="[191,286,319,343]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68">holotype</typeStatus>
, which unfortunately has a slightly damaged apex of the abdomen. However, the rest of the preapical bulge on the last ventrite is visible, so that it is possible to attribute it to a species with a distinctly bifurcate male metasternum in agreement with 
<bibRefCitation author="LABOISSIERE V." box="[878,1086,383,407]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" pagination="783 - 790" refId="ref8741" refString="LABOISSIERE V. 1922 a: Chrysomelides (supplement). Voyage de M. le baron Maurice de Rothschild en Ethiopie et en Afrique Orientale Anglaise (1904 - 1905) 2: 783 - 790." type="journal article" year="1922">LABOISSIÈRE (1922a)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
